... I haven't sold any for a while.

64
00:07:09,305 --> 00:07:11,974
Since when do you not like
macaroni and cheese?

65
00:07:12,183 --> 00:07:14,721
Since birth?

66
00:07:17,188 --> 00:07:19,228
- What's that?
- What?

67
00:07:19,441 --> 00:07:22,525
- What is this?
- It's a gift for Christopher.

68
00:07:22,736 --> 00:07:25,227
- From who?
- Cynthia from work.

69
00:07:25,447 --> 00:07:28,532
It's for adults. Chris can't use it.
She didn't know.

70
00:07:28,742 --> 00:07:30,735
What are you supposed
to do with it?

71
00:07:31,453 --> 00:07:34,538
Make every side the same colour.

72
00:07:35,833 --> 00:07:38,122
Did you pay the taxes?

73
00:07:38,419 --> 00:07:41,539
No, I'm gonna
have to file an extension.

74
00:07:42,340 --> 00:07:46,468
- You already filed an extension.
- Yeah, well, I gotta file another one.

75
00:07:46,845 --> 00:07:50,546
That's... It's $650.
I'll have it in the next month.

76
00:07:51,058 --> 00:07:52,885
That means interest, right?

77
00:07:53,101 --> 00:07:55,474
- And a penalty?
- Yeah, a little bit.

78
00:07:55,688 --> 00:08:01,311
Look, why don't you let me do this?
All right, just relax. Okay?

79
00:08:01,527 --> 00:08:05,655
- Come here. Calm down.
- I have to go back to work.

80
00:08:13,707 --> 00:08:17,325
Let's get ready for bed.
Hey, put your plate in the sink.

81
00:08:18,045 --> 00:08:20,962
A few days ago I was presented
with a report I'd asked for...

82
00:08:21,173 --> 00:08:24,874
... a comprehensive audit, if you will,
of our economic condition.

83
00:08:25,553 --> 00:08:28,304
You won't like it. I didn't like it.

84
00:08:28,514 --> 00:08:30,174
But we have to face the truth...

85
00:08:30,391 --> 00:08:33,013
... and then go to work
to turn things around.

86
00:08:33,227 --> 00:08:36,976
And make no mistake about it,
we can turn them around.

87
00:08:37,190 --> 00:08:40,274
The federal budget is out of control.

88
00:08:40,485 --> 00:08:43,854
And we face runaway deficits
of almost $80 billion...

89
00:08:44,072 --> 00:08:47,488
... for this budget year
that ends September 30th.

90
00:08:47,701 --> 00:08:52,909
That deficit is larger than
the entire federal budget in 1957.

91
00:08:53,124 --> 00:08:55,697
And so is the almost $80 billion...

92
00:08:55,918 --> 00:09:00,212
... we will pay in interest
this year on the national debt.

93
00:09:00,840 --> 00:09:03,378
Twenty years ago, in 1960...

94
00:09:03,593 --> 00:09:07,721
... our federal government payroll
was less than $13 billion.

95
00:09:07,931 --> 00:09:10,636
Today it is 75 billion.

96
00:09:10,851 --> 00:09:16,391
During these 20 years, our population
has only increased by 23.3 percent...

97
00:09:34,584 --> 00:09:37,336
Man, I got two questions for you:

98
00:09:37,546 --> 00:09:40,666
What do you do?
And how do you do it?

99
00:09:42,176 --> 00:09:45,260
- I'm a stockbroker.
- Stockbroker. Oh, goodness.

100
00:09:45,471 --> 00:09:47,428
Had to go to college
to be a stockbroker, huh?

101
00:09:47,723 --> 00:09:51,424
You don't have to. Have to be good
with numbers and good with people.

102
00:09:51,644 --> 00:09:54,016
- That's it.
- Hey, you take care.

103
00:09:54,230 --> 00:09:56,270
I'll let you hang on to my car
for the weekend.

104
00:09:56,482 --> 00:09:58,938
- But I need it back for Monday.
- Feed the meter.

105
00:10:06,159 --> 00:10:08,532
I still remember that moment.

106
00:10:12,833 --> 00:10:17,460
They all looked
so damn happy to me.

107
00:10:24,679 --> 00:10:27,051
Why couldn't I look like that?

108
00:10:44,659 --> 00:10:45,987
I'm gonna try to get home by 6.

109
00:10:46,202 --> 00:10:49,322
I'm gonna stop by a brokerage firm
after work.

110
00:10:49,539 --> 00:10:52,825
- For what?
- I wanna see about a job there.

111
00:10:53,042 --> 00:10:55,664
Yeah? What job?

112
00:10:56,171 --> 00:10:58,164
You know, when I...

113
00:10:58,381 --> 00:11:01,003
When I was a kid, I could go through
a math book in a week.

114
00:11:01,218 --> 00:11:04,552
So I'm gonna go see about
what job they got down there.

115
00:11:05,681 --> 00:11:07,590
What job?

116
00:11:10,561 --> 00:11:12,305
Stockbroker.

117
00:11:14,607 --> 00:11:17,810
- Stockbroker?
- Yeah.

118
00:11:18,236 --> 00:11:20,193
Not an astronaut?

119
00:11:37,214 --> 00:11:38,709
Don't talk to me like that, Linda.

120
00:11:39,842 --> 00:11:43,626
I'm gonna go down and see about this,
and I'm gonna do it during the day.

121
00:11:43,846 --> 00:11:45,554
You should probably
do your sales calls.

122
00:11:46,015 --> 00:11:48,423
I don't need you to tell me
about my sales calls, Linda.

123
00:11:48,643 --> 00:11:51,847
I got three of them
before the damn office is even open.

124
00:11:52,397 --> 00:11:54,805
Do you remember
that rent is due next week?

125
00:11:55,025 --> 00:11:56,899
Probably not.

126
00:11:57,528 --> 00:11:59,567
We're already two months behind.

127
00:11:59,780 --> 00:12:02,817
Next week we'll owe three months.

128
00:12:03,284 --> 00:12:07,412
I've been pulling double shifts
for four months now, Chris.

129
00:12:07,830 --> 00:12:12,124
Just sell what's in your contract.
Get us out of that business.

130
00:12:12,335 --> 00:12:16,036
Linda, that is what I am trying to do.

131
00:12:16,798 --> 00:12:19,468
This is what I'm trying to do
for my family...

132
00:12:19,676 --> 00:12:21,052
...for you and for Christopher.

133
00:12:22,471 --> 00:12:24,594
What's the matter with you?

134
00:12:28,769 --> 00:12:30,429
Linda.

135
00:12:31,021 --> 00:12:32,564
Linda.

136
00:12:59,552 --> 00:13:04,629
This part of my life
is called "Being Stupid."

137
00:13:06,684 --> 00:13:07,965
Can I ask you a favour, miss?

138
00:13:08,186 --> 00:13:12,054
Do you mind if I leave this here
with you just for five minutes?

139
00:13:12,274 --> 00:13:14,765
I have a meeting in there
and I don't wanna carry that...

140
00:13:14,985 --> 00:13:16,978
...looking smalltime.

141
00:13:17,821 --> 00:13:22,282
Here is a dollar and I'll give you
more money when I come back out.

142
00:13:22,493 --> 00:13:25,743
Okay? It's not valuable.
You can't sell it anywhere.

143
00:13:26,706 --> 00:13:31,831
I can't even sell it, and it's my job.
All right? Be right back.

144
00:13:38,551 --> 00:13:40,877
- Chris? Tim Brophy, Resources.
- Yes. How are you?

145
00:13:41,096 --> 00:13:42,424
- Follow me.
- Yes, sir.

146
00:13:42,639 --> 00:13:45,391
Let me see if I can find you
an application for our internship.

147
00:13:45,601 --> 00:13:48,851
I'm afraid that's all we can do for you.
See, this is a satellite office.

148
00:13:49,063 --> 00:13:51,684
Jay Twistle in the main office,
he oversees Witter Resources.

149
00:13:51,899 --> 00:13:54,022
I mean, I'm... You know,
I'm just this office.

150
00:13:54,235 --> 00:13:57,152
As you can see, we got a hell of lot
of applications here, so...

151
00:13:57,363 --> 00:14:00,364
Normally I have a résumé sheet,
but I can't seem to find it anywhere.

152
00:14:00,575 --> 00:14:03,991
- We...
- Thank you very much.

153
00:14:04,204 --> 00:14:05,366
I need to go.

154
00:14:05,956 --> 00:14:07,664
I'll bring this back.

155
00:14:07,916 --> 00:14:11,036
- Thank you.
- Okay.

156
00:14:17,426 --> 00:14:21,887
Trusting a hippie girl with my scanner.
Why did I do that?

157
00:14:22,098 --> 00:14:23,722
Excuse me. Excuse me.

158
00:14:23,933 --> 00:14:29,390
Like I said, this part of my life
is called "Being Stupid."

159
00:14:32,567 --> 00:14:37,276
Hey! Hey! Hey! Don't move!
Don't move! Stay...!

160
00:14:45,247 --> 00:14:47,573
Stop! Stop!

161
00:14:47,792 --> 00:14:50,995
Don't move!
Stop this...! Stop the train!

162
00:14:52,046 --> 00:14:54,335
Stop! Stop!

163
00:15:09,273 --> 00:15:12,974
The programme took just 20 people
every six months.

164
00:15:13,194 --> 00:15:15,270
One got the job.

165
00:15:16,822 --> 00:15:22,197
There were three blank lines after
"high school" to list more education.

166
00:15:23,746 --> 00:15:26,534
I didn't need that many lines.

167
00:15:31,630 --> 00:15:34,631
Try and sleep. It's late.

168
00:15:44,602 --> 00:15:48,185
It's a puzzle measuring just 3 inches
by 3 inches on each side...

169
00:15:48,398 --> 00:15:50,805
... made up of multiple colours
that you twist and turn...

170
00:15:51,025 --> 00:15:53,647
... and try to get
to a solid colour on each side.

171
00:15:53,862 --> 00:15:57,480
This little cube
is the gift sensation of 1981.

172
00:15:57,699 --> 00:15:59,075
Don't expect to solve it easily.

173
00:15:59,284 --> 00:16:01,692
Although we did encounter
one math professor at USF...

174
00:16:01,912 --> 00:16:04,403
... who took just 30 minutes on his.

175
00:16:04,623 --> 00:16:06,830
This is as far as I've gotten
on mine.

176
00:16:07,042 --> 00:16:10,412
As you can see,
I still have a long way to go.

177
00:16:10,630 --> 00:16:13,251
This is Jim Finnerty reporting
for KJSF in Richmond.

178
00:16:13,466 --> 00:16:16,171
Hey, wake up.

179
00:16:16,386 --> 00:16:17,880
Eat.

180
00:16:19,013 --> 00:16:21,469
- Bye, Mom.
- Bye, baby.

181
00:16:21,683 --> 00:16:24,684
- Come back without that, please.
- Oh, yeah, I'm going to.

182
00:16:24,895 --> 00:16:27,812
So go ahead, say goodbye to it,
because I'm coming back without it.

183
00:16:28,023 --> 00:16:30,431
Goodbye and good riddance.

184
00:16:30,651 --> 00:16:32,608
You ain't had to add
the "good riddance" part.

185
00:16:32,820 --> 00:16:33,851
Bye, Mom.

186
00:16:35,406 --> 00:16:36,734
Bye.

187
00:16:36,949 --> 00:16:40,532
It's written as P-P-Y, but it's
supposed to be an I in "happiness."

188
00:16:40,745 --> 00:16:43,865
- Is it an adjective?
- No, actually it's a noun.

189
00:16:44,082 --> 00:16:45,825
But it's not spelled right.

190
00:16:46,042 --> 00:16:49,625
- Is "fuck" spelled right?
- Yeah, that's spelled right.

191
00:16:49,838 --> 00:16:52,958
But that's not part of the motto,
so you're not supposed to learn that.

192
00:16:53,175 --> 00:16:58,051
That's an adult word to show anger
and other things.

193
00:16:58,263 --> 00:17:01,134
- But just don't use that one, okay?
- Okay.

194
00:17:01,350 --> 00:17:03,509
What's that say
on the back of your bag?

195
00:17:03,853 --> 00:17:05,810
My nickname.

196
00:17:06,022 --> 00:17:07,599
We pick nicknames.

197
00:17:07,815 --> 00:17:11,184
- Oh, yeah? What's it say?
- "Hot Rod."

198
00:17:14,197 --> 00:17:16,237
- Did you have a nickname?
- Yep.

199
00:17:16,449 --> 00:17:19,154
- What?
- "Ten-Gallon Head."

200
00:17:19,369 --> 00:17:22,240
- What's that?
- I grew up in Louisiana, near Texas.

201
00:17:22,456 --> 00:17:27,083
Everybody wears cowboy hats.
And a ten-gallon's a big hat.

202
00:17:27,294 --> 00:17:30,877
I was smart back then,
so they called me Ten-Gallon Head.

203
00:17:31,465 --> 00:17:33,588
- Hoss wears that hat.
- Hoss?

204
00:17:33,885 --> 00:17:35,593
Hoss Cartwright on Bonanza.

205
00:17:36,054 --> 00:17:39,589
- How do you know Bonanza?
- We watch it at Mrs. Chu's.

206
00:17:40,266 --> 00:17:43,351
- You watch Bonanza at daycare?
- Yeah.

207
00:17:44,437 --> 00:17:46,477
When? When do you watch it?

208
00:17:46,690 --> 00:17:50,355
- After snack? After your nap?
- After Love Boat.

209
00:17:55,282 --> 00:17:57,441
I made my list for my birthday.

210
00:17:58,202 --> 00:18:02,745
- Yeah, what'd you put on there?
- A basketball or an ant farm.

211
00:18:06,336 --> 00:18:10,630
- He says he's been watching TV.
- Oh, little TV for history.

212
00:18:10,841 --> 00:18:13,925
- Love Boat?
- For history. Navy.

213
00:18:14,636 --> 00:18:16,380
That's not the Navy.

214
00:18:16,597 --> 00:18:18,720
I mean, he could
watch television at home.

215
00:18:18,932 --> 00:18:23,310
We're paying you $150 a month.
If he's gonna be sitting around...

216
00:18:23,521 --> 00:18:25,893
...watching TV all day,
we're taking him out of here.

217
00:18:26,107 --> 00:18:29,891
Go pay more at other daycare
if you don't like Navy TV.

218
00:18:31,779 --> 00:18:36,987
You late pay anyway.
You complain. I complain.

219
00:18:38,495 --> 00:18:42,279
Can you at least put the dog upstairs
in your room or something?

220
00:18:42,499 --> 00:18:43,958
Bye.

221
00:19:28,339 --> 00:19:32,207
I was waiting for
Witter Resource head Jay Twistle...

222
00:19:32,469 --> 00:19:37,974
... whose name sounded so delightful,
like he’d give me a job and a hug.

223
00:19:38,183 --> 00:19:42,181
I just had to show him I was good
with numbers and good with people.

224
00:19:42,396 --> 00:19:43,938
- Morning, Mr. Twistle.
- Good morning.

225
00:19:44,148 --> 00:19:45,559
- Mr. Twistle, Chris Gardner.
- Hi.

226
00:19:45,775 --> 00:19:48,562
I wanted to drop this off personally
and make your acquaintance.

227
00:19:48,778 --> 00:19:52,147
I thought I'd catch you on the way in.
I'd love the opportunity to discuss...

228
00:19:52,365 --> 00:19:54,571
...what may seem like weaknesses
on my application.

229
00:19:54,784 --> 00:19:57,572
We'll start with this, and we'll call you
if we wanna sit down.

230
00:19:57,787 --> 00:20:00,742
- Yes, sir. You have a great day.
- You too.

231
00:20:07,798 --> 00:20:09,423
Hey, yeah, how you doing?

232
00:20:09,633 --> 00:20:11,792
This is Chris Gardner calling
for Dr. Delsey.

233
00:20:12,011 --> 00:20:14,169
Yeah, I'm running a little late
for a sales call.

234
00:20:14,388 --> 00:20:17,888
I was wondering if...
Yeah, Osteo National.

